<TITLE> Police rescue endangered sea turtles from old Dhaka </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 28 (bdnews24.com)  Police said they rescued two sea turtles of an endangered species from Tantibazar in old Dhaka Friday. The turtles were found for sale in a market, sub inspector SM Swapan of Kotwali Police Station told bdnews24.com. Md Abdus Samad, director of the department of environment's coastal and wetland biodiversity management project, confirmed to bdnews24.com that they were endangered. "They are sea turtles are of an endangered species," he said, adding that they were known as Olive Ridley turtles. The number of turtle of this species is decreasing alarmingly, he said and that selling endangered animals was a criminal offence. Police arrested a man named Mamun, who had brought the sea turtles to the market to sell. Department of environment public relations officer Abdullah Zahiruddin said the turtles were very weak but that steps were being taken to release them in the sea. They would eventually regain their health and reproduce, he said. Officials of the department of environment went to Old Dhaka Friday morning, on a tip-off, and called the police after they found the turtles on sale. bdnews24.
